Using Avro with a Schema Registry is an excellent choice for ensuring consistency and versioning of your event schemas in a distributed system. This approach helps maintain data integrity across different services and simplifies the process of handling schema changes over time. Below are steps to integrate Avro and Confluent's Schema Registry into your Spring Boot application, along with guidelines on how producers should register their schemas before sending messages.

### 1. Add Dependencies

First, add the necessary dependencies for Kafka, Avro, and Schema Registry support in your `pom.xml` or `build.gradle`.

#### Maven
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.confluent</groupId>
    <artifactId>kafka-avro-serializer</artifactId>
    <version>7.1.0</version> <!-- Use the latest version -->
</dependency>

<!-- Optional: Spring Cloud Stream for easier integration with Kafka -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-stream-binder-kafka</artifactId>
    <version>3.2.0</version> <!-- Use a compatible version -->
</dependency>
```

### 2. Configure Schema Registry

Configure the Kafka producer and schema registry in your `application.properties`.

```properties
# Kafka configuration
spring.kafka.bootstrap-servers=localhost:9092
spring.kafka.producer.key-serializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
spring.kafka.producer.value-serializer=io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroSerializer

# Schema Registry configuration
spring.kafka.properties.schema.registry.url=http://localhost:8081
```

### 3. Define Avro Schemas

Define your Avro schemas for the events you will be sending. For example, create an `OrderCreatedEvent.avsc` schema file:

```json
{
    "namespace": "com.example.order",
    "type": "record",
    "name": "OrderCreatedEvent",
    "fields": [
        {"name": "order_id", "type": "string"},
        {"name": "customer_id", "type": "string"},
        {"name": "items", "type": {
            "type": "array",
            "items": {
                "type": "record",
                "name": "OrderItem",
                "fields": [
                    {"name": "product_id", "type": "string"},
                    {"name": "quantity", "type": "int"}
                ]
            }
        }},
        {"name": "total_amount", "type": "double"},
        {"name": "created_at", "type": "long"} // Unix timestamp
    ]
}
```

### 4. Create Kafka Producer Configuration Class

Create a configuration class to set up the Kafka producer with Avro serialization.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerConfig;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class KafkaProducerConfig {

    @Value("${spring.kafka.properties.schema.registry.url}")
    private String schemaRegistryUrl;

    @Bean
    public ProducerFactory<String, OrderCreatedEvent> producerFactory() {
        Map<String, Object> configProps = new HashMap<>();
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, KafkaAvroSerializer.class);

        // Configure schema registry URL
        configProps.put(AbstractKafkaSchemaSerDeConfig.SCHEMA_REGISTRY_URL_CONFIG, schemaRegistryUrl);

        return new DefaultKafkaProducerFactory<>(configProps);
    }

    @Bean
    public KafkaTemplate<String, OrderCreatedEvent> kafkaTemplate() {
        return new KafkaTemplate<>(producerFactory());
    }
}
```

### 5. Create a Service to Publish Events

Create a service class that uses the `KafkaTemplate` to publish Avro events.

```java
import org.apache.avro.Schema;
import org.apache.avro.generic.GenericRecord;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerRecord;
